Article 12}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049\rtlch \ltrch\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch
  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
(1) The mineral resources, the mines, power plants, dams and large bodies of water, the natural riches of the continental shelf, larger industrial companies, banks and insurance institutions, the nationally owned goods, the traffic routes, the means of transport of the railroad, the sea and the aviation, the postal and Telecommunications systems are public property. Private ownership of it is not permitted.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch
  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
(2) The socialist state guarantees the use of public property with the aim of achieving the highest result for society. This is what the socialist planned economy and socialist economic law serve. The use and management of public property is generally carried out by the state-owned companies and state institutions. The state can transfer its use and management through contracts to cooperative or social organizations and associations. Such a transfer has to serve the interests of the general public and the increase of social wealth.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049\rtlch \ltrch\loch

